x found in the disc membranes of rod photoreceptor outer segments. It consists of two catalytic subunits, PDE6A and PDE6B, and two inhibitory gamma-subunits, PDE6G. In response to activation by transducin, the complex hydrolyzes cyclic GMP, thereby mediating the light-induced closure of cGMP-gated ion channels during rod phototransduction.\" [PMID:38159849]\nsynonym: \"rod PDE6 complex\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"rod photoreceptor PDE6 complex\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0032991 ! protein-containing complex\nrelationship: part_of GO:0120202 ! rod photoreceptor disc membrane\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31081\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: dragon-ai-agent\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770031\nname: sodium ion sequestering activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Binding to a sodium ion to prevent it from interacting with other partners or to inhibit its localization to the area of the cell or complex where it is active.\" [PMID:25689889]\nintersection_of: GO:0140313 ! molecular sequestering activity\nintersection_of: has_part GO:0031402 ! sodium ion binding\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31137\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: dragon-ai-agent\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770032\nname: obsolete tyramine transport\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"OBSOLETE. The directed movement of tyramine into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Tyramine is a monoamine neurotransmitter occurring predominantly in invertebrates.\" [PMID:15849736, PMID:32305263, PMID:9870940]\ncomment: The reason for obsoletion is that this is an unnecessary grouping term and annotations should be made to more mechanism/location specific terms.\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31143\" xsd:anyURI\nis_obsolete: true\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770033\nname: octopamine transport\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The directed movement of octopamine into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Octopamine is a monoamine neurotransmitter occurring predominantly in invertebrates.\" [PMID:15849736, PMID:32305263, PMID:9870940]\nintersection_of: GO:0006810 ! transport\nintersection_of: has_primary_input CHEBI:58025 ! octopaminium\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31143\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: dragon-ai-agent\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770034\nname: nickel-pincer nucleotide cofactor biosynthetic process\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nickel-pincer nucleotide (NPN) cofactor, also known as nickel pyridinium-3,5-bisthiocarboxylic acid mononucleotide.\" [PMID:24710389, PMID:27114550, PMID:33093595, PMID:39667499, PMID:39827451]\nsynonym: \"NPN cofactor biosynthetic process\" EXACT []\nxref: MetaCyc:PWY-7928 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: MetaCyc:PWY-8561 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0051191 ! prosthetic group biosynthetic process\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31252\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31634\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: dragon-ai-agent\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770035\nname: negative regulation of ER to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of ER to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport.\" [PMID:21693198]\nintersection_of: GO:0065007 ! biological regulation\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates GO:0006888 ! endoplasmic reticulum to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/31273\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: dragon-ai-agent\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:7770036\nname: flavin transferase activity\nnamespac